      "writtenOn": "2017-05-26T15:31:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Interestingly, removing the reinterpret_cast leads to different binary code when compiling for A32 (32-bit ARM):\n\n  3b4:\tf4c0080f \tvst1.32\t{d16[0]}, [r0]\n  3b4:\tf4c0083f \tvst1.32\t{d16[0]}, [r0 :32]  // \u003c-- without reinterpret_cast\u003cuint8_t*\u003e\n\nSo this code will generate an alignment exception if dst is not 4 bytes aligned. Normally, I would expect that src and dst are always correctly aligned. But this may introduce a risk of regression if some code in the wild is incorrectly using this function. Should we take this risk?",
      "parentUuid": "437f4939_942cbcb9",
